ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The portion of the aorta following the aortic arch passing into the chest and abdomen creating the thoracic and abdominal segments.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Tendons that connect the papillary muscles to the tricuspid valve and mitral valve.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The three small bones in the middle ear that transmit acoustic vibrations from the eardrum to the inner ear.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A lymph node located in the superior mediastinum that collects lymph from the thymus, the pericardium, and the right side of the heart.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The area that includes the anus and the perianal skin.

Concepts.definition: The area that includes the anus and the perianal skin.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A ridge or ridge-like structure.  In humans it usually refers to the trachea.  The carina of trachea is part of the lowest tracheal cartilage which is placed between the orifices of the two bronchi.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Stiff sensory hair that projects outward from the body.

Concepts.definition: Stiff sensory hair that projects outward from the body.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Fibrous joints between the bones of the skull.

Concepts.definition: Fibrous joints between the bones of the skull.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The superior portion of the occipital bone on the dorsal side of the great foramen of the skull; it is present during fetal development and later fuses with the occipital bone.

Concepts.definition: The superior portion of the occipital bone on the dorsal side of the great foramen of the skull; it is present during fetal development and later fuses with the occipital bone.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A muscle in the posterior forearm that originates from the posterior proximal shaft of ulna and the lateral epicondyle of humerus and attaches to the proximal third of the radius on the anterolateral and posterior surface; it functions to supinate the forearm.

Concepts.definition: A muscle in the posterior forearm that originates from the posterior proximal shaft of ulna and the lateral epicondyle of humerus and attaches to the proximal third of the radius on the anterolateral and posterior surface; it functions to supinate the forearm.

Concepts.definition: The tissue that forms the wall of the stomach. It consists of mucosa, submucosa, muscular coat, and serosal surface.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The parenchyma of the spinal cord, which consists of a canal surrounded by a neuron containing gray matter centrally and white matter containing myelinated nerve tracts peripherally.

Concepts.definition: The parenchyma of the spinal cord, which consists of a canal surrounded by a neuron containing gray matter centrally and white matter containing myelinated nerve tracts peripherally.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The projection on the anterior part of the face that includes the nose or nose and mouth.

Concepts.definition: The projection on the anterior part of the face that includes the nose or nose and mouth.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: One of two cranial bones that by their union form the sides and roof of the skull.

Concepts.definition: One of two cranial bones that by their union form the sides and roof of the skull.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The trapezoidal-shaped bone that forms the back and part of the base of the skull.

Concepts.definition: The trapezoidal-shaped bone that forms the back and part of the base of the skull.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Bile ducts are passageways that carry bile. Two major bile ducts come together into a "trunk"-the common bile duct which empties into the upper part of the small intestine (the part next to the stomach).

Concepts.definition: Bile ducts are passageways that carry bile. Two major bile ducts come together into a "trunk"-the common bile duct which empties into the upper part of the small intestine (the part next to the stomach).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: (BRON-kee-olz) The tiny branches of air tubes in the lungs.

Concepts.definition: The smallest subdivisions of the bronchial tree, which are both acartilagenous and aglandular.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A sloped depression between the dorsum sellae and foramen magnum at the base of the skull.

Concepts.definition: A sloped depression between the dorsum sellae and foramen magnum at the base of the skull.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The inner layer of the connective tissue that seals the joint.

Concepts.definition: The inner layer of the connective tissue that seals the joint.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A type of connective tissue composed of chondrocytes and an extracellular matrix, composed of collagen, elastin, and ground substance. There are three types of cartilage; namely elastic, hyaline, and fibrocartilage.

Concepts.definition: A type of connective tissue composed of chondrocytes and an extracellular matrix, composed of collagen, elastin, and ground substance. There are three types of cartilage; namely elastic, hyaline, and fibrocartilage.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A broad fold of peritoneum that extends from the side of the uterus to the wall of the pelvis. (MeSH)

Concepts.definition: A wide fold of peritoneum that connects the uterus to the lateral walls and floor of the pelvis, and contains the ovaries, fallopian tubes, ovarian ligaments, round ligament of the uterus, and ovarian and uterine arteries.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The fleshy lobe that hangs at the back of the soft palate.

Concepts.definition: The fleshy lobe that hangs at the back of the soft palate.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The posterior one third of the tongue behind the terminal sulcus that forms the anterior aspect of the oro-pharynx responsible for swallowing and modification of the voice in speech.

Concepts.definition: The posterior one third of the tongue behind the terminal sulcus that forms the anterior aspect of the oro-pharynx responsible for swallowing and modification of the voice in speech.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The junction where the tissue of the atrial septum and the ventricular septum meet.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The wall that separates the aorta and pulmonary arteries during embryonic development.

Concepts.definition: The wall that separates the aorta and pulmonary arteries during embryonic development.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The distal portion of the gastrointestinal tract that includes the anal canal and rectum.

Concepts.definition: The distal portion of the gastrointestinal tract that includes the anal canal and rectum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A small muscle in the posterior elbow that originates from the lateral epicondyle of the humerus and attaches to the lateral surface of the olecranon of the ulna; it functions to extend the forearm and stabilize the elbow joint.

Concepts.definition: A small muscle in the posterior elbow that originates from the lateral epicondyle of the humerus and attaches to the lateral surface of the olecranon of the ulna; it functions to extend the forearm and stabilize the elbow joint.

Concepts.definition: A muscle of the hand that extends from the capitate and bases of the second and third metacarpals for the oblique head, and the anterior surface of body of the third metacarpal for the transverse head, to the base of proximal phalanx and extensor hood of the thumb; primary function is to draw the first metacarpal laterally to oppose the thumb toward the center of palm and rotate it medially.

Concepts.definition: A lymph node outside the abdominal cavity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The internal and external muscles surrounding the anus that maintain continence.

Concepts.definition: The internal and external muscles surrounding the anus that maintain continence.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The posterior surface of the glottic opening at the level of the vocal cords.

Concepts.definition: The posterior surface of the glottic opening at the level of the vocal cords.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any non-hardened or non-calcified tissue found in the periorbital area.

Concepts.definition: Any non-hardened or non-calcified tissue found in the periorbital area.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any non-hardened or non-calcified tissue found in the nose.

Concepts.definition: The mucus membrane lining the inner surface of the colon.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The clear, watery fluid which fills the anterior and posterior chambers of the eye. (Cline et al., Dictionary of Visual Science, 4th ed, p319)

Concepts.definition: The watery fluid which is present in the anterior and posterior chambers of the eye.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The fluid within the amniotic cavity which surrounds and protects the developing embryo.  It is initially produced by the amnion and then later by the lungs and kidneys.  The amount at term normally varies from 500 to 2000 ml.

Concepts.definition: The fluid within the amniotic cavity which surrounds and protects the developing embryo. It is initially produced by the amnion and then later by the lungs and kidneys. The amount at term normally varies from 500 to 2000 ml.

Concepts.definition: A muscle of mastication originating from the zygomatic arch.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A band of fibrous connective tissue that joins bone to muscle.

Concepts.definition: A band of fibrous connective tissue that joins bone to muscle.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any component of the female organs and tissues involved in the production and maturation of gametes and in their union and subsequent development as offspring.

Concepts.definition: Any component of the female organs and tissues involved in the production and maturation of gametes and in their union and subsequent development as offspring.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The junction of the common bile and main pancreatic ducts, which protrudes into the medial aspect of the descending duodenum at the major duodenal papilla. The flow of bile and pancreatic juices into the duodenum through the Ampulla of Vater is controlled by the sphincter of Oddi.

Concepts.definition: A muscle in the back that originates from the nuchal ligament and spinal processes of the seventh cervical and first thoracic vertebrae and attaches to the medial border of the scapula; along with the rhomboid major muscle, it functions to stabilize and retract the scapula.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A muscle in the back that originates from the spinous processes of the second to fifth thoracic vertebrae and attaches to the medial border of the scapula; along with the rhomboid minor muscle, it functions to stabilize and retract the scapula.

Concepts.definition: A muscle in the back that originates from the spinous processes of the second to fifth thoracic vertebrae and attaches to the medial border of the scapula; along with the rhomboid minor muscle, it functions to stabilize and retract the scapula.

Concepts.definition: A group of muscles that function to extend the ankle, flexing the foot downward toward the sole, and includes the gastrocnemius, soleus, plantaris, tibialis posterior, flexor hallucis longus, and flexor digitorum longus muscles.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A short muscle in the lateral compartment of the lower leg that originates on the distal two-thirds of the lateral surface of the fibula and the anterior intermuscular septum, attaches to the tuberosity of the fifth metatarsal bone, and functions to plantar flex and evert the foot.

Concepts.definition: A short muscle in the lateral compartment of the lower leg that originates on the distal two-thirds of the lateral surface of the fibula and the anterior intermuscular septum, attaches to the tuberosity of the fifth metatarsal bone, and functions to plantar flex and evert the foot.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The space surrounding the meninges.

Concepts.definition: The space surrounding the meninges.

Concepts.definition: A lymph node located adjacent to the trachea within the mediastinum, above the inferior margin of the left brachiocephalic vein crossing the trachea on the left and the superior border of the aortic arch on the right.

Concepts.definition: A group muscles in the sole of the foot that originate from the tendons of the flexor digitorum longus muscle and attach to the medial bases of the proximal phalanges and the extensor expansion of the second through fifth digits; they function to flex and adduct the lateral four toes at the metatarsophalangeal joints and extend them at the interphalangeal joints.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A group of muscles that function to flex the knee, including the sartorius, popliteus, gastrocnemius, gracilis, semi-tendinosis, semi-membranosis, and bicep femoris muscles.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A bone of the hindpaw.

Concepts.definition: A bone of the hindpaw.

Concepts.definition: The anatomical space of the cardiac ventricle.

Concepts.definition: A muscle in the posterior forearm that originates from the posterior surface of the middle third of the ulna and the adjacent interosseous membrane and attaches to the posterior surface of the base of distal phalanx of the thumb; it functions to extend the thumb at the metacarpophalangeal and interphalangeal joints and extend and abduct the wrist joint.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A muscle in the posterior forearm that originates from the posterior surface of distal third of radius and the adjacent interosseous membrane and attaches to the posterior surface of the base of the proximal phalanx of the thumb; it functions to extend the thumb at the carpometacarpal and metacarpophalangeal joints.

Concepts.definition: A muscle in the posterior forearm that originates from the posterior surface of distal third of radius and the adjacent interosseous membrane and attaches to the posterior surface of the base of the proximal phalanx of the thumb; it functions to extend the thumb at the carpometacarpal and metacarpophalangeal joints.

Concepts.definition: A muscle in the lower extremity that originates from the middle third of the medial surface of the fibula and the adjacent interosseous membrane and attaches to the base and dorsal center of the distal phalanx of the great toe; it functions to extend the big toe and dorsiflex the ankle.

Concepts.definition: A muscle in the posterior forearm that originates from the lateral epicondyle of the humerus and attaches to the extensor expansion of the fifth digit; it functions to extend the fifth digit at the metacarpophalangeal joint.

Concepts.definition: A peripheral nerve that runs close to the small saphenous vein. It supplies innervation to the skin of the lower back of the leg and sends a branch to the lateral side of the foot and little toe.

Concepts.definition: The more superficial of the two muscles (peroneus longus and peroneus brevis) of the lateral compartment of the lower leg, which originates at the superior, lateral shaft of the fibula and inserts on the first metatarsal and the medial cuneiform, functioning to plantar flex and evert the foot, and which supports the lateral, longitudinal, and transverse arches.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Mucosa arranged into two fundamental structures - villi and crypts of Lieberkuhn. Villi are projections into the lumen of the small intestine, covered with simple columnar epithelium. Crypts of Lieberkuhn are moat-like invaginations of the epithelium around the villi that extend through the lamina propria down to the muscularis mucosae. Lymphocytes often invade the epithelium or form solitary lymphoid nodules in the lamina propria. Lymph nodules may form longitudinal aggregations of 30-50 nodules in the lamina propria of the ileum. These large aggregations are called Peyer's patches. The muscularis mucosae has two layers and extends into the intestinal villi, where the smooth muscle cells form a longitudinal bundle in the centre of the villi. The small intestinal mucosa secretes gastrin, somatostatin, cholecystokinin and secretin.

Concepts.definition: Mucosa arranged into two fundamental structures - villi and crypts of Lieberkuhn. Villi are projections into the lumen of the small intestine, covered with simple columnar epithelium. Crypts of Lieberkuhn are moat-like invaginations of the epithelium around the villi that extend through the lamina propria down to the muscularis mucosae. Lymphocytes often invade the epithelium or form solitary lymphoid nodules in the lamina propria. Lymph nodules may form longitudinal aggregations of 30-50 nodules in the lamina propria of the ileum. These large aggregations are called Peyer's patches. The muscularis mucosae has two layers and extends into the intestinal villi, where the smooth muscle cells form a longitudinal bundle in the centre of the villi. The small intestinal mucosa secretes gastrin, somatostatin, cholecystokinin and secretin.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A large cell mass extending forward, over the dorsal surface of the crus cerebri, from the rostral border of the pons into the subthalamic region. It is composed of a dorsal stratum of closely spaced pigmented cells, the pars compacta, and a larger ventral region of widely scattered cells, the pars reticulata. The pars compacta includes numerous cells that project forward to the striatum (caudate nucleus and putamen) and contain dopamine, which acts as the primary neurotransmitter at the synaptic endings. Other, apparently non-dopaminergic cells project to portions of the ventral nucleus of thalamus, the superior colliculus and reticular formation. The nigrostriatal projection is reciprocated by a striatonigral fiber system with multiple neurotransmitters, chief among which is gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA). The substantia nigra is involved in the metabolic disturbances associated with Parkinson's disease and Huntington's disease.

Concepts.definition: A large cell mass extending forward, over the dorsal surface of the crus cerebri, from the rostral border of the pons into the subthalamic region. It is composed of a dorsal stratum of closely spaced pigmented cells, the pars compacta, and a larger ventral region of widely scattered cells, the pars reticulata. The pars compacta includes numerous cells that project forward to the striatum (caudate nucleus and putamen) and contain dopamine, which acts as the primary neurotransmitter at the synaptic endings. Other, apparently non-dopaminergic cells project to portions of the ventral nucleus of thalamus, the superior colliculus and reticular formation. The nigrostriatal projection is reciprocated by a striatonigral fiber system with multiple neurotransmitters, chief among which is gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA). The substantia nigra is involved in the metabolic disturbances associated with Parkinson's disease and Huntington's disease.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An organ behind the lower part of the stomach that is the shape of a fish and about the size of a hand. It is a compound gland composed of both exocrine and endocrine tissues. The endocrine pancreas makes insulin so that the body can use glucose (sugar) for energy. The exocrine pancreas makes enzymes that help the body digest food. Spread all over the pancreas are areas called the Islets of Langerhans. The cells in these areas each have a special purpose. The alpha cells make glucagon, which raises the level of glucose in the blood; the beta cells make insulin; the delta cells make somatostatin. There are also PP cells and D1 cells, about which little is known.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An organ that is part of the lymphatic system, in which T lymphocytes grow and multiply. The thymus is in the chest behind the breastbone.

Concepts.definition: A bi-lobed organ surrounded by a connective tissue capsule. It is located in the upper anterior portion of the chest, behind the sternum. It is composed predominantly of lymphocytes and fewer epithelial cells. Connective tissue septa separate the lobes into lobules. The lobules contain an outer portion (cortical zone) which is rich in lymphocytes and an inner portion (medullary zone) which is rich in epithelial cells. It is an organ essential for the development of the immune system. Its function is the maturation of the progenitor lymphoid cells to thymocytes and subsequently to mature T-cells. It reaches its greatest weight at puberty and subsequently begins to involute.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An important supervisory center in the brain, rich in ganglia, nerve fibers, and synaptic connections. It is composed of several sections called nuclei, each of which controls a specific function. The hypothalamus regulates body temperature, blood pressure, heartbeat, metabolism of fats and carbohydrates, and sugar levels in the blood. Through direct attachment to the pituitary gland, the hypothalamus also meters secretions controlling water balance and milk production in the female. The role of the hypothalamus in awareness of pleasure and pain is well established in the laboratory. It is involved in the expression of emotions, such as fear and rage, and in sexual behaviors. Despite its numerous vital functions, the hypothalamus in humans accounts for only 1/300 of total brain weight, and is about the size of an almond. Structurally, it is joined to the thalamus; the two work together to monitor the sleep-wake cycle.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A blind pouch-like commencement of the colon in the right lower quadrant of the abdomen at the end of the small intestine and the start of the large intestine.

Concepts.definition: A blind pouch-like commencement of the colon in the right lower quadrant of the abdomen at the end of the small intestine and the start of the large intestine.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The major arterial trunk that carries oxygenated blood from the left ventricle into the ascending aorta behind the heart, the aortic arch, through the thorax as the descending aorta and through the abdomen as the abdominal aorta; it bifurcates into the left and right common iliac arteries.

Concepts.definition: The major arterial trunk that carries oxygenated blood from the left ventricle into the ascending aorta behind the heart, the aortic arch, through the thorax as the descending aorta and through the abdomen as the abdominal aorta; it bifurcates into the left and right common iliac arteries.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A lymph node located adjacent to the lumbar region of the spine.

Concepts.definition: A lymph node located adjacent to the lumbar region of the spine.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The broad, dorsal, upper, and widest of the three principal bones composing either half of the pelvis.

Concepts.definition: The broad, dorsal, upper, and widest of the three principal bones composing either half of the pelvis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any of the bundles of nerve fibers running to various organs and tissues of the body using chemical and electrical signals to transmit sensory and motor information from one body part to another.

Concepts.definition: Part of the peripheral nervous system composed of bundles of nerve fibers running to various organs and tissues of the body using chemical and electrical signals to transmit sensory and motor information from one body part to another.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The large vein that carries blood from the head, neck, arms, and chest to the heart.

Concepts.definition: The large vein that terminates in the right atrium and transports deoxygenated blood from the head, neck, arms, and chest to the heart.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any of the round ligaments including the round ligament of the liver and the round ligament of the uterus.

Concepts.definition: Any of the round ligaments including the round ligament of the liver and the round ligament of the uterus.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A part of the ear canal that is external to the ear drum.

Concepts.definition: A part of the ear canal that is external to the ear drum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A muscle group in the hand that controls radial extension and abduction or deviation of the wrist; either the extensor carpi radialis brevis muscle, which originates at the lateral epicondyle of the humerus and inserts at the third metacarpal bone, or the extensor carpi radialis longus muscle, which originates at the lateral supracondylar ridge of the humerus and inserts at the back base of the second metacarpal bone.

Concepts.definition: A muscle group in the hand that controls radial extension and abduction or deviation of the wrist; either the extensor carpi radialis brevis muscle, which originates at the lateral epicondyle of the humerus and inserts at the third metacarpal bone, or the extensor carpi radialis longus muscle, which originates at the lateral supracondylar ridge of the humerus and inserts at the back base of the second metacarpal bone.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The most distal end of the finger.

Concepts.definition: The most distal end of the finger.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A shallow groove in the shaft of the humerus through which the radial nerve and deep brachial artery course.

Concepts.definition: A shallow groove in the shaft of the humerus through which the radial nerve and deep brachial artery course.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The portion of the maxillary jaw bone and other facial bones that form the most lateral mid face skeletal structure.

Concepts.definition: The portion of the maxillary jaw bone and other facial bones that form the most lateral mid face skeletal structure.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The portion of the cingulate gyrus that lies inferior to the superior frontal gyrus, and is separated from it by the cingulate sulcus; it ends inferior to the rostrum of the corpus callosum.

Concepts.definition: The portion of the cingulate gyrus that lies inferior to the superior frontal gyrus, and is separated from it by the cingulate sulcus; it ends inferior to the rostrum of the corpus callosum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A superficial neck muscle and a key anatomical landmark, which divides the neck into anterior and lateral regions. It originates on the manubrium and the clavicle, and inserts onto the mastoid process and the superior nuchal line. It functions to flex the neck, move the chin cranially, and assists in elevating the rib cage during inspiration.

Concepts.definition: A superficial neck muscle and a key anatomical landmark, which divides the neck into anterior and lateral regions. It originates on the manubrium and the clavicle, and inserts onto the mastoid process and the superior nuchal line. It functions to flex the neck, move the chin cranially, and assists in elevating the rib cage during inspiration.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A group of three muscles (iliocostalis, longissimus, and spinalis) that originate at the sacrum, ilium, and lumbar vertebrae spines and insert into the ribs and vertebra in order to extend the vertebral column.

Concepts.definition: A group of three muscles (iliocostalis, longissimus, and spinalis) that originate at the sacrum, ilium, and lumbar vertebrae spines and insert into the ribs and vertebra in order to extend the vertebral column.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A fibrous band extending from the distal end of the quadriceps femoris to the top of the patella.

Concepts.definition: A fibrous band extending from the distal end of the quadriceps femoris to the top of the patella.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: One of four veins that carries oxygen-rich blood from the lungs to the cardiac left atrium.

Concepts.definition: One of four veins that carries oxygen-rich blood from the lungs to the cardiac left atrium.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The potential body space between the arachnoid membrane and the dura mater.

Concepts.definition: The potential body space between the arachnoid membrane and the dura mater.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Area consisting of a small depression in the retina containing only cones and where vision is most acute.

Concepts.definition: Area consisting of a small depression in the retina containing only cones and where vision is most acute.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: One of two major branches of the sciatic nerve. It innervates the muscles of the posterior aspect of the lower limb, the muscles of the plantar aspect of the foot, as well as the skin on the posterior aspect of the leg and on the sole of the foot.

Concepts.definition: One of two major branches of the sciatic nerve. It innervates the muscles of the posterior aspect of the lower limb, the muscles of the plantar aspect of the foot, as well as the skin on the posterior aspect of the leg and on the sole of the foot.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any one of the three (common, deep, and superficial) peroneal nerves.

Concepts.definition: Any one of the three (common, deep, and superficial) peroneal nerves.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The part of the pelvic wall that is formed by the piriformis and obturator internus muscles and contains the iliac vessels, pelvic ureters, and lateral pelvic lymph nodes.

Concepts.definition: The part of the pelvic wall that is formed by the piriformis and obturator internus muscles and contains the iliac vessels, pelvic ureters, and lateral pelvic lymph nodes.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A group of lymph nodes located in the inferior part of the mediastinum.

Concepts.definition: A group of lymph nodes located in the inferior part of the mediastinum.

PermissibleValues.value: SUPERIOR MEDIASTINAL LYMPH NODE LEVEL VII

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Superior Mediastinal Lymph Node Group (Level VII)
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Lymph nodes in this group include pretracheal, paratracheal, and esophageal groove lymph nodes, extending from the level of the suprasternal notch cephalad and up to the innominate artery caudad. These nodes are at greatest risk of involvement by thyroid cancer and cancer of the esophagus. (AJCC 8th ed.)

Concepts.longName: Superior Mediastinal Lymph Node Group (Level VII)
Concepts.definition: Lymph nodes in this group include pretracheal, paratracheal, and esophageal groove lymph nodes, extending from the level of the suprasternal notch cephalad and up to the innominate artery caudad. These nodes are at greatest risk of involvement by thyroid cancer and cancer of the esophagus. (AJCC 8th ed.)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Dura mater - the outermost, toughest, and most fibrous of the three membranes (meninges) that surround and protect the brain and spinal cord.

Concepts.definition: The outermost, toughest, and most fibrous of the three membranes (meninges) that surround and protect the brain and spinal cord.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An anatomic structure formed by the crossing of the two optic nerves under the hypothalamus.

Concepts.definition: An anatomic structure formed by the crossing of the two optic nerves under the hypothalamus.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A lymph node that is found within the parenchyma of the lung.

Concepts.definition: A lymph node that is found within the parenchyma of the lung.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An artery formed by the union of the two vertebral arteries at the posterior border of the pons then diverges at the anterior border forming the two superior and two posterior cerebral arteries.

Concepts.definition: An artery formed by the union of the two vertebral arteries at the posterior border of the pons then diverges at the anterior border forming the two superior and two posterior cerebral arteries.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: White matter pathway, flanked by nuclear masses, consisting of both afferent and efferent fibers projecting between the cerebral cortex and the brainstem. It consists of three distinct parts: the anterior limb, posterior limb, and genu. (MeSH)

Concepts.definition: A white matter structure in the subcortical region of the brain that contains a high concentration of motor and sensory projection nerve fibers. It consists of the anterior limb, genu, posterior limb, and the retrolentiform and sublentiform parts.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The region of the abdomen that extends from the median plane to the left of the patient, and from the umbilical plane to the left ribcage.

Concepts.definition: The region of the abdomen that extends from the median plane to the left of the patient, and from the umbilical plane to the left ribcage.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The region of the abdomen that extends from the median plane to the right of the patient, and from the umbilical plane to the right ribcage.

Concepts.definition: The region of the abdomen that extends from the median plane to the right of the patient, and from the umbilical plane to the right ribcage.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The region of the abdomen that extends from the median plane to the right of the patient, and from the umbilical plane to the right inguinal ligament.

Concepts.definition: The region of the abdomen that extends from the median plane to the right of the patient, and from the umbilical plane to the right inguinal ligament.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A thin lamina of white matter comprising long association fibers located between the claustrum and putamen in the brain, and which connects the midportion of the superotemporal region with the midportion of the ventral and lateral aspects of the prefrontal cortex.

Concepts.definition: A thin lamina of white matter comprising long association fibers located between the claustrum and putamen in the brain, and which connects the midportion of the superotemporal region with the midportion of the ventral and lateral aspects of the prefrontal cortex.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A continuation of the femoral artery that descends behind the knee joint before branching into the anterior and posterior tibial arteries.

Concepts.definition: A continuation of the femoral artery that descends behind the knee joint before branching into the anterior and posterior tibial arteries.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The joint between the left and right pubic bones at the front of the pelvis.

Concepts.definition: The joint between the left and right pubic bones at the front of the pelvis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any of the eight ligaments pertaining to the uterus including the anterior, posterior, lateral, sacro-uterine and round ligaments.

Concepts.definition: Any of the eight ligaments pertaining to the uterus including the anterior, posterior, lateral, sacro-uterine and round ligaments.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The small amount of fluid that is generated in the abdominal cavity to lubricate the peritoneum.

Concepts.definition: The small amount of fluid that is generated in the abdominal cavity to lubricate the peritoneum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The fluid that is ordinarily present in the pleural space. It allows for normal movement of the lungs during respiration.

Concepts.definition: The fluid that is ordinarily present in the pleural space. It allows for normal movement of the lungs during respiration.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The cavity just below the bladder where the prostate gland is located.

Concepts.definition: The cavity just below the bladder where the prostate gland is located.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The region of the abdomen that extends from the median plane to the left of the patient, and below the umbilicus.

Concepts.definition: The region of the abdomen that extends from the median plane to the left of the patient, and below the umbilicus.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The anterosuperior part of the bladder that points towards the abdominal wall.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The large area of the bladder situatedbetween the apex and the fundus.

Concepts.definition: The large area of the bladder situated between the apex and the fundus.

Concepts.definition: The portion of the thoracic esophagus from the thoracic inlet to the level of the tracheal bifurcation. (SEER)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The medial segment of the left lobe of the liver.

Concepts.definition: The medial segment of the left lobe of the liver.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The integument that covers the area above the eyebrow.

Concepts.definition: The integument that covers the area above the eyebrow.

Concepts.definition: The integument that covers the area directly below the eye.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The portion of the thoracic esophagus from the tracheal bifurcation midway to the gastroesophageal junction. (SEER)

Concepts.definition: The portion of the thoracic esophagus from the tracheal bifurcation midway to the gastroesophageal junction. (SEER)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The striated muscle tissue of the heart enveloped by the epicardium and the endocardium.

Concepts.definition: The striated muscle tissue of the heart enveloped by the epicardium and the endocardium.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The largest of the ethmoidal nasal turbinates, extending from the ethmoidal crest into the middle of the nasal cavity.

Concepts.definition: The largest of the ethmoidal nasal turbinates, extending from the ethmoidal crest into the middle of the nasal cavity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An opening in the medial portion of the middle cranial fossa through which the trigeminal nerve passes.

Concepts.definition: An opening in the medial portion of the middle cranial fossa through which the trigeminal nerve passes.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The inferior portion of the right ventricle of the heart.

Concepts.definition: The inferior portion of the right ventricle of the heart.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The central portion of the right ventricle of the heart.

Concepts.definition: The central portion of the right ventricle of the heart.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The portion of the internal capsule of the brain that is located posterior to the genu.

Concepts.definition: The portion of the internal capsule of the brain that is located posterior to the genu.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: One of the two arteries arising from the internal carotid artery and being part of the Circle of Willis. Both left and right anterior cerebral arteries are connected by the anterior communicating artery.

Concepts.definition: One of the two arteries arising from the internal carotid artery and being part of the Circle of Willis. Both left and right anterior cerebral arteries are connected by the anterior communicating artery.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The posterior cerebral artery is formed by the bifurcation of the basilar artery; it divides into three branches.

Concepts.definition: The posterior cerebral artery is formed by the bifurcation of the basilar artery; it divides into three branches.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Arteries which have their origins within the intracranial cavity.

Concepts.definition: Arteries which have their origins within the intracranial cavity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any portion of the body that lies outside of a lymph node.

Concepts.definition: Any portion of the body that lies outside of a lymph node.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The outermost of the two pleural membranes. It consists of a thin basal layer of fibrous tissue upon which sits a continuous layer of mesothelial cells. The cells function to secrete the lubricant lining the pleural cavity.

Concepts.definition: The outermost of the two pleural membranes. It consists of a thin basal layer of fibrous tissue upon which sits a continuous layer of mesothelial cells. The cells function to secrete the lubricant lining the pleural cavity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Either of a pair of nerves that arise in the cervical plexus and provide innervation of the diaphragm.

Concepts.definition: Either of a pair of nerves that arise in the cervical plexus and provide innervation of the diaphragm.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The largest terminal branch of the internal carotid artery that runs along the fissure of Sylvius with branches supplying parts of the fontal, parietal and temporal lobes as well as the basal ganglia and internal capsule.

Concepts.definition: The largest terminal branch of the internal carotid artery that runs along the fissure of Sylvius with branches supplying parts of the fontal, parietal and temporal lobes as well as the basal ganglia and internal capsule.
